eenth century—especially cholera—and that they reflect the long institutional memories embodied in public health institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAIDS (Disease)xDeveloped countries. 0aAIDS (Disease)zDeveloped countries. 7aMEDICAL / Health Policy.2bisacsh  aacquired immune deficiency syndrome.  aaids epidemic.  aaids.  aamerican government.  acholera.  acommunity safety.  acontagious disease.  ademocracy.  adiscrimination.  aeurope.  aeuropean governments.  agovernments and governing.  ahealth.  ahistorical.  ahiv.  ahuman immunodeficiency virus infection.  aillness.  aimmune system.  aindividual liberty.  ainstitutional memory.  amedical conditions.  amedicine.  apolitical.  apolitics.  apublic health practices.  apublic healthcare.  asocial impacts.  aunited states of america.  awestern democracy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094079640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520940796423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520940796/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles